Nice I can give you a single, copy-pasteable set of terminal commands (with a few helpful checks) that will deploy tmosimanyana/moofarsite to Netlify from your machine using the Netlify CLI.

Quick notes before the commands

  • The repo already contains a netlify.toml and a public folder (so it looks set up for a static publish). GitHub

  • The commands below install the Netlify CLI, log you in, run a build (if the repo has a package.json with a build script), detect the correct publish directory (public, dist, or build) and then deploy to production with the Netlify CLI. The Netlify CLI deploy flow and the --dir / --prod flags are documented by Netlify. Netlify Docs+1

  • If you want continuous deploys from GitHub instead of manual CLI deploys, use Netlifys New site from Git UI (or netlify init / link a site with the CLI). Build settings / publish directory choices are covered in Netlify docs. Netlify Docs+1

Copy-paste this into your terminal (bash / macOS / Linux). Read comments in the script and run each block step-by-step if you prefer.

bash
# 1) Clone the repo
git clone https://github.com/tmosimanyana/moofarsite.git
cd moofarsite

# 2) If this repo uses Node and has a package.json, install deps and run build (if it has a build script)
if [ -f package.json ]; then
  echo "package.json found -> installing dependencies"
  npm install

  # if there's a "build" script, run it
  if grep -q '"build"[[:space:]]*:' package.json; then
    echo "build script found -> running npm run build"
    npm run build || { echo "npm run build failed  check build errors"; exit 1; }
  else
    echo "no build script detected in package.json"
  fi
else
  echo "no package.json  assuming static files are present (e.g. in public/)"
fi

# 3) Detect a likely publish directory (public, dist, or build)
PUBLISH_DIR=""
for d in public dist build; do
  if [ -d "$d" ]; then
    PUBLISH_DIR="$d"
    break
  fi
done
if [ -z "$PUBLISH_DIR" ]; then
  echo "Could not find public/ dist/ or build/ directory. Please set the directory that contains your site files."
  echo "Listing repo files:"
  ls -la
  exit 1
fi
echo "Using publish directory: $PUBLISH_DIR"

# 4) Install Netlify CLI (global) if you don't have it
if ! command -v netlify >/dev/null 2>&1; then
  echo "Installing netlify-cli (requires node and npm)..."
  npm install -g netlify-cli
else
  echo "netlify CLI already installed: $(netlify --version)"
fi

# 5) Login to Netlify (browser will open to authorize)
echo "Logging into Netlify..."
netlify login

# (Optional) If you want to create/link a Netlify site interactively:
# netlify init
# or to link to an existing site:
# netlify link

# 6) Deploy to Netlify (production)
# This will upload the files in $PUBLISH_DIR; Netlify will also honor netlify.toml or _redirects if present.
netlify deploy --prod --dir="$PUBLISH_DIR"

# On success you'll get a production URL returned in the output.

What each step does (short)

  • npm install -g netlify-cli: installs the official Netlify CLI. Netlify Docs

  • netlify login: authenticates your CLI to your Netlify account. Netlify Docs

  • netlify deploy --prod --dir=...: uploads the chosen directory and deploys it as a production deploy. If your repo includes netlify.toml (it does), Netlify will process redirects and function config from there. Netlify CLI command reference+1

  • If you want CI/CD (auto-builds when you push to GitHub), use Netlifys Add new site from Git in the Netlify UI or netlify init and follow the prompts set the build command and publish dir there (or inside netlify.toml). Netlify Docs+1

Troubleshooting tips

  • If netlify deploy complains about missing files, double-check the PUBLISH_DIR you used (adjust to public, dist, or build as appropriate).

  • If your project requires environment variables or a specific build-image / node version, set those in the Netlify UI under Site settings Build & deploy, or add appropriate settings to netlify.toml. Netlify Docs

  • To see logs for a build/deploy, use the deploy URLs returned by the CLI or the Netlify UI deploy logs. Netlify CLI command reference

Perfect heres how to run the interactive Netlify deploy flow on Windows 11 using PowerShell or Command Prompt.

Prerequisites

  1. Install Node.js + npm

    • Get it from https://nodejs.org/ (choose the LTS version).

    • After install, open a new PowerShell and run:

      powershell
      node -v
npm -v

      Both should show version numbers.

  2. Install Git

    • Download: https://git-scm.com/download/win

    • Verify with:

      powershell
      git --version

Step-by-step commands for PowerShell

Copypaste these lines one block at a time in PowerShell:

powershell
# 1  Clone the repository
git clone https://github.com/tmosimanyana/moofarsite.git
cd moofarsite

# 2  If the project uses Node.js, install dependencies
if (Test-Path package.json) {
  Write-Host "package.json found  installing dependencies..."
  npm install

  # Run build if there is a build script
  $pkg = Get-Content package.json | Out-String
  if ($pkg -match '"build"\s*:') {
    Write-Host "Build script detected  running npm run build..."
    npm run build
  } else {
    Write-Host "No build script found  skipping build step."
  }
} else {
  Write-Host "No package.json found  assuming static site (e.g. public/)."
}

# 3  Detect publish directory
$publishDirs = @("public","dist","build")
$publishDir = $publishDirs | Where-Object { Test-Path $_ } | Select-Object -First 1
if (-not $publishDir) {
  Write-Host " No public/dist/build folder found  check project structure!"
  exit
}
Write-Host " Using publish directory: $publishDir"

# 4  Install Netlify CLI globally if needed
if (-not (Get-Command netlify -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue)) {
  npm install -g netlify-cli
} else {
  netlify --version
}

# 5  Login to Netlify (this will open a browser)
netlify login

# 6  Deploy interactively
# Use init if you want to link or create a Netlify site
netlify init

# 7  Deploy to production
netlify deploy --prod --dir=$publishDir

What happens during the flow

  1. netlify login opens your browser to authenticate.

  2. netlify init lets you pick an existing Netlify site or create a new one linked to your GitHub repo.

  3. netlify deploy --prod uploads your built/static site to production.

After deployment

  • The CLI will print your live URL, e.g.

    csharp
      Deploy is live!
https://moofarsite.netlify.app

  • You can then manage the site in your Netlify dashboard:
    https://app.netlify.com/sites

Ah thats a PowerShell execution policy issue, not an npm problem.
Windows blocks .ps1 scripts (like npm.ps1) when PowerShells execution policy is too restrictive.

Lets fix it safely

Fix: Allow npm (and similar tools) to run in PowerShell

Option 1 Easiest, temporary (just for this session)

Run this in PowerShell as Administrator:

powershell
Set-ExecutionPolicy -Scope Process -ExecutionPolicy Bypass

Then try again:

powershell
npm -v

If that works, you can continue with npm install, npm run build, etc.

This setting resets automatically when you close PowerShell safe and recommended.

Option 2 Permanent for your user (optional)

If you want npm to always work without repeating the fix, run:

powershell
Set-ExecutionPolicy -Scope CurrentUser -ExecutionPolicy RemoteSigned -Force

Explanation:

  • RemoteSigned lets locally created scripts run freely.

  • It still blocks downloaded scripts unless theyre signed, keeping your system secure.

Option 3 Use CMD instead

You can also just open a normal Command Prompt (not PowerShell) and run:

cmd
npm -v

npm works fine there because CMD doesnt enforce PowerShells execution policy.

Once npm works (you see a version number like 10.8.2), go back to the deployment steps.

pgsql
You are now logged in to Netlify!

  1. Disable ad blockers, uBlock, Ghostery, or Brave Shields temporarily.

    arduino

    powershell

moofar.js handles IntersectionObserver:

function animateOnScroll() {
  const elements = document.querySelectorAll('[data-animate]');
  const observer = new IntersectionObserver(entries => {
    entries.forEach(entry => {

    });

  elements.forEach(el => observer.observe(el));
}

moofar.js

javascript
// -------------------- MOBILE MENU --------------------
function toggleMenu() {
  const nav = document.querySelector('nav ul');
  const btn = document.querySelector('.menu-btn');
  const expanded = btn.getAttribute('aria-expanded') === 'true';
  btn.setAttribute('aria-expanded', !expanded);
  nav.classList.toggle('open');
}

// Close mobile menu when clicking outside
document.addEventListener('click', (e) => {
  const nav = document.querySelector('nav ul');
  const menuBtn = document.querySelector('.menu-btn');
  if (nav && nav.classList.contains('open') && !nav.contains(e.target) && !menuBtn.contains(e.target)) {
    nav.classList.remove('open');
    menuBtn.setAttribute('aria-expanded','false');
  }
});

// -------------------- SCROLL ANIMATIONS --------------------
function animateOnScroll() {
  const elements = document.querySelectorAll('[data-animate]');
  const observer = new IntersectionObserver(entries => {
    entries.forEach(entry => {
      if (entry.isIntersecting) entry.target.classList.add('visible');
    });
  }, { threshold: 0.2 });
  elements.forEach(el => observer.observe(el));
}

// -------------------- PARALLAX HERO --------------------
function initParallax() {
  const hero = document.querySelector('.hero-section');
  if (!hero) return;
  window.addEventListener('scroll', () => {
    const scrolled = window.pageYOffset;
    hero.style.backgroundPosition = `center ${scrolled * 0.5}px`;
  });
}

// -------------------- INIT --------------------
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
  animateOnScroll();
  initParallax();
});
